\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid11750969 Sir Raymond Firth
\par Summary
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
\par 7 January 2000
\par 
\par Born 25 March 1901, Auckland, New Zealand, in Millais Street (which he used to think was Malay Street).  Then to Mount St John's Avenue, until aged 9. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6699985 Afterwards}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6699985 moved }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 to the country, 40 miles south, Patumahoe, at a local primary school, until aged 13.
\par 
\par Sums himself up as Emeritus Professor of Anthropology at the University of London and Life President of the Associati}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16533651 on of Social Anthropologists.  \lquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 I think it's clear I'm not a public figure'.  David Schneider has said he is not a major intellectual figure either, beca}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16533651 use he did not produce \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
spectacular theories'.   Worked with Schneider on kinship, and criticises him for knowing the answers before he loo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16533651 ked at the fieldwork material. \lquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 The spectacular idea attracts attention, but isn't necessarily a contribution to the subject itself, in the end'.  H}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16533651 is own contributions have been \lquote rather low-key', \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
pedestrian'.  Perhaps the most important in economic anthropology; also kinship, and religion.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6699985 Edmund Leach said, \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
all ethnography is fiction'.  Certainly there is always a personal contribution }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6699985 added by the ethnographer, but \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 I believe, quite definitely, that there is a factual world behind\'85 and one's job is to try and reach that factual world by observation and infere}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6699985 nce.  Conversely, you can say, \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 all fiction is
 ethnography'.  Anthropologists are concerned with people's fantasies, literature, oral traditions, myths.  Isaac Schapera on Jane Aust}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6699985 
en.  Maybe it is all illusion, \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 but one has to assume there is a real world'.
\par 
\par Father from Townsendfold, Rawtenstall, Lan
cashire; grandfather a small merchant, china shop, carpentry.  Grandfather widowed, remarried, decided to emigrate to New Zealand with new wife and child and Raymond's father, and also grandfather's three brothers, of whom two went to Australia.  When gra
ndfather died father was in his teens and had to earn - as a boilermaker.  Then when grand-stepmother also died, father joined up as a builder with great-uncle Henry: proved very successful, c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15887296 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  1910 one of first builders in New Zealand to use reinforced con
crete.  Died aged 104 in 1977.
\par 
\par Mother died in 1962 aged 86.  Grandfather an Ulster Orangeman, already in New Zealand when met grandmother, a doctor's daughter on a trip from England}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15887296 
.  Later farmed as pioneers in \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 the bush'.
\par 
\par Their own farm, 365 acres, was in disorder when th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15601481 ey came, father put it right \endash  \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 tidy-minded man'.  Four horse plough to pull out the gorse.  Father hoped Raymond w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15601481 
ould be a farmer, but soon saw \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 that letters attracted me'.  Rode to school on own horse Darkie bare-footed because of th
e mud, picking up the family mail and reading the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Wide World Magazine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  on the way home on a grassy bank.
\par 
\par Father a wise man.  Had a temper.  Broke in young horses, built houses, ordered the farm.  Gave Raymond a model of objective judgement, neutrality, tolerance.  Not very religious, although called Wesley,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15601481  and attended Methodists.  Saw c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 reation as a complex 
issue.  Easy to talk to.  A kind of closeness, but also reserve.
\par 
\par Mo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15601481 ther much more emotional, held \lquote alarming opinions'.  Spoke \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 loudly' against war.  Had been a violinist.  A loving woman, but also a stro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15601481 
ng temper.  Could talk to her, \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 I think so'.  But he was away for much of his childhood.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15601481 On the farm, \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
very much a farm boy', had to bring in the seven or eight horses to feed them before going to school.  Left in paddock attached to the school with nosebag of chaff and oats.
\par 
\par Mauku School unusual, and als
o its headmaster, Gutrie.  School garden hemmed in with planks which they had to make with proper curves.  Long lunch breaks with games and races through the countryside.  At 13, with not much encouragement won a Junior National Scholarship to Auckland Gr
ammar School, 40 miles away, so had to stay with friends.  From there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12087640  won}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12087640 a Senior National Scholarship \endash \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 never at the top, always about}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12087640  three or more down'.  Later a u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 niversity Scholarship.
\par 
\par Younger sister died at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12087640 2 of pneumonia, for his mother \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 a most bitter, bitter thing'; he remem}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12087640 bers her calling out her name, \lquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 "Greta, Greta, Greta." Very moving.'
\par 
\par Younger brother Cedric, seven years younger, followed father: builder-carpenter, then architect.  Took a degree at RIBA in London, became well-known in Wellington NZ, also in musical life.
\par 
\par Father a builder not an architect, but did draw plans: built by day and plans by night.  Took up part-time farming for health reasons.  Only horses, no tractor or steam plough.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4394366 They h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
ad their own forge.  Two men, Gilmore and Brady, did ploughing, planting, harvesting.  Neighbours helped at harvest, around 20, brought own horses and wagons, mother would cook for them. Children would help with sleighs.  Mixed farming, sheep, beef cattle
, milk cows, oats, rye.  Raymond learnt to milk, and to shoot rabbits with a .22 at the age of ten.
\par 
\par Local church shared by Methodists and Presbyterians.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4394366 Attended S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 undays only, wore shoes.  One store and Post Office three miles away; not much gossip there,
 but a meeting place for the coach to the railway station nine miles on.  Had to ride nine miles to get a doctor.  No bar for drinks anywhere.  Conventional rather than puritan social atmosphere.
\par 
\par Maori settlements not close at hand.  His own first interest sparked by finding Frederick Maning's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Old New Zealand}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  in a bookshop: Maning had been a judge in the Native Land Court, married to a Maori chief's daughter.  Started reading the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Journal of the Polynesian Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 in the public library aged 15, became inter
ested in anthropology, and began to learn Maori with James Rukutai, a court interpreter.  In next five years sought out remnants of Maori meeting houses with carved wood, etc.  At 22 a week's walking trip entirely through Maori territory, down the Whakata
ne River, staying in a village which he has photographed for one of his books.  Maori land claims based on 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  century Treaty of Waitangi.  Judgements in courts are partly based on oral tradition: Fenton, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Judgements of the Native land Court}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .
\par 
\par Few memories of Auckland before moving to the country.  Went to Remuera School in a pinafore.  The family house was quite large, with a white }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4394366\charrsid13782781 
veranda}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  and a red corrugated iron roof.  Also built by father.
\par 
\par Auckland Grammar School.  First headmaster, Tibbs, taught mathe
matics, conventional-minded.  Second headmaster, English teacher, Mahon, became his mentor and asked him back later to teach.  Read a lot in public library and school library, including Richard Burton: had a taste for the exotic as well as for ethnography
 and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Journal of the Polynesian Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .  
\par 
\par Also read in Auckland Institute.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Captain Cook's Voyages}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  maybe later. Certainly Rivers }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 History of Melanesian Society}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .  Among novels, Kipling, Belloc, Evelyn Waugh, Dickens, Scott, Kingsley, Ballantyne.
\par 
\par Best friend at school was Edgar Burton, later journalist on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 New Zealand Herald}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
.  Lived with them when he went to school.  Boisterous family.  Mr Burton older, almost blind.  Eldest son Osmund gifted, officer in war, later in church; Dorothy had bad health; Eddie,
 his friend; and Robert, the youngest. Leslie Munro another friend.  Robert Falla, later director of  National Museum of New Zealand, ornithologist: used to go together to coast looking for sea birds. Also formed a group of four or five studying abandoned
 Maori hill fort, and published an article on this.
\par 
\par Never interested in national politics; international, yes.
\par 
\par Earlier, himself a Methodist.  After the farm, parents settled at Otara, a sheep area ten miles from Auckland, with many Polynesian immigrants, 
and a bad reputation for violence.  Church community there important: became Sunday School Superintendent; father also active, treasurer.  Church picnics on the beach.  No alcohol, no dancing: only learned to dance at university.  Then a practising Christ
ian, but bit by bit it slipped.
\par 
\par Studied English, chemistry and economics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12679793  at Auckland University}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .  Carried on with some organic chemistry for three years, but not strongly enough drawn to it.  English was straightforward, from Anglo-Saxon to Pope, too dry. 
 Economics really quite interesting: taught by Grossman, highly intellectual (sad end to career, debt and horses), who had to teach history and politics as well.  External examiner was J. M. Keynes, by post, very tough: gave him 35, two above pass level. 
 Decided to go on to do a master's by thesis, on Kauri gum.  A fossil resin, which had to be dug out.  Spent several weeks on the gum fields talking to the diggers.  Examiner J.S. Nicholson of Edinburgh gave 95%.  So Master's with First Class Honours.

\par 
\par The next year, while teaching at the Grammar School, did a Diploma in Social Science, taught by William Anderson, scholarly (brother was flamboyant philosopher in Sydney): very helpful, included psychology and philosophy.
\par 
\par At the Grammar School taught form 3C.  Also an officer in school cadets: and was a good sho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7229139 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7229139 er}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  with a rifle.
\par 
\par At home, kept on riding and sailing a dinghy in the Tamaki River.
\par 
\par Father saw that he would not make a farmer and his heart was rather in research, so he agreed to give him \'a3
250 a year for three years.  Got a free passage for students on a cargo liner, mainly carrying butter and meat, to London.  Went to LSE, which he chose because it was the college for social science, registered, intending to read economics, but professor w
as away on vacation, so asked about anthropology.  Forcibly struck by being introduced to Malinowski, whose work he had already discovered: in combining economics and anthropology }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Argonauts of the Western Pacific }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
did just what he thought he would like to do
.  But as the preface was from the Canary Islands he had no idea Malinowski was at LSE.  For six months studied both subjects, then opted for anthropology - although there seemed few job prospects in the subject - and worked with Malinowski until 1927.

\par 
\par Malinowski was more impressive in a seminar than in a lecture.  Superb as a seminar leader: the seed bed of the mind.  Continually analysing, questioning, focussing on the problem.  Some students gave papers.  Students included Evans-Pritchard, Ashley Mon
tague (later Columbia), Barbara Freire-Mareco, Ursula Grant-Duff; later}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9510094 , Talcott Parsons, Hortense Pow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 dermaker, Schapera.
\par 
\par Malinowski one of the most powerful intellectual influences on him.  Vivid memories of those years.  Contrasting temperaments: Malinow
ski sparkling, outgoing, adroit in handling people, but a loyal friend, far-reaching in imagination, with a touch of melancholy, a great medicine-taker.  By contrast himself sober, judicious, reserved, more tentative in generalisations. 
\par 
\par Much to do with students outside the classroom.  (Could show unrestrained anger. In the end Evans-Pritchard became an enemy, described Malinowski's theories as futile.)  Made him welcome in his home, and also in their villa in Oberbozen/Soprabolzano.

\par 
\par Malinowski criticised
 him for not showing feelings enough. But later parted company on theory of culture and basic needs, and also differed on which courses should be taught.  But he could talk about these differences.  Perhaps only Rivers - whom he never knew - had this psyc
h
ological dimension to anthropology.  Malinowski also unusual in England for his command of European languages: French, German, Spanish, Italian, Polish.  Contrasted with more insular Marett at Oxford and Haddon at Cambridge.  Malinowski's friends also inc
luded Europeans: Marcel Mauss in Paris (whom he got to know moderately well), Preuss and Richard Thurnwald in Germany.
\par 
\par Some English anthropologists had also not learnt the local language for fieldwork: Layard, Radcliffe Brown.  But not unusual for New Zeal
and anthropologists to know Maori: Elsdon Best, Edwin Smith. Missionaries too.  Malinowski did not invent fieldwork in social anthropology, but in systematised the perception of it.
\par 
\par Evans-Pritchard he liked very much.  Professionally E-P saw him as a rival, but personally they remained friends, dining and staying together. Originally }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12324890 
he was called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 just Pritchard. Letters with affectionate endings, suggesting they should become blood brothers.
\par 
\par There was a great deal of camaraderie between men.  Friendship was highly regarded, without homosexual connotations that they were aware of.
\par 
\par Michael/Munia Postan, economic history professor at Cambridge, his greatest friend in England: walked and climbed together, borrowed his house in Cambridge in the war: a considerable influence, brilliant, also with a continental vision.
\par 
\par At LSE Isaac Schapera one of his oldest friends, came from South Africa, built up the LSE department together.  Ashley Montague went to Columbia University: American, wild, dramatic.
\par 
\par Camilla Wedgwood came from Cambridge to LSE, became a very good friend, saw the proofs of his first book through the press.  Lectured for him in Sydney.
\par 
\par Ursula Grant-Duff, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1771764 met her for lunch in London, once}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  with admiral, general, retired diplomat, fishing stories.  Stayed with her cousin Jo Pitt-Rivers, grandson of the General, a follower of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1771764\charrsid13782781 Nietzsche}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
, arrogant but interesting, had researched in New Guinea, first mentioned Durkheim to him.
\par 
\par Lady Frances Ryder, daughter of Earl of Harrowby, organised country house week
ends for Commonwealth students.  He went to Sir Robert Williams MP at Bridehead, Dorset.  Very interesting: servants, butler, gamekeeper, cricket week, calling cards, very paternalistic. At Christmas Sir Robert took round }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1771764 joints of beef and scuttles of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 coa
l to the tenants: reprimanded for taking a photo of this, and for taking notes.  Beauty of winter landscape new to him.
\par 
\par Stayed with Malinowski four times, some for weeks, at the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1771764 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid1771764 pfarrhaus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1771764 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 a mile from Oberbozen villa: the old priest had a magnificent coo
k who taught others.  Walked over to Malinowski for tea and discussion: often sitting nude on his balcony scrubbing himself with a salt concoction.  Magnificent view of Dolomites. Sometimes parties with local people shoe-dancing.  Other visitors included 
Evans-Pritchard in 1925, Schapera.  Always came by plane, various ways, including Berlin, Vienna, Venice (which Malinowski loved).
\par 
\par At Verona, San Zeno stimulated his fascination for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14044981\charrsid13782781 Romanesque}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  sculpture and painting.  Has a shelf of books on this.
\par 
\par Saw only a little of Italian etc social life or politics. Had learnt French in New Zealand, and now began to read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 L'Ann\'e9e sociologique}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14044981 . While at}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 LSE learnt German and read a lot, including Marx.
\par 
\par In 1924-7 not many lectures at LSE.  Malinowski, Seligman did give some, and himself later.  But the real impact was from Mal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14044981 
inowski's regular seminars.  Everyone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  read papers in the seminars, or chapters of their theses.
\par 
\par For his thesis, thought of studying Polynesian economics as a whole, but there was enough Maor
i material, so concentrated on that.  Used no manuscript sources, just printed sources, and his own knowledge.  Worked for three years in seat L5 of British Museum Library.  He was the first professional anthropologist to write about the Maori.  His objec
tive not to provide documentation, for which there was already a century of writing - for example, describing Maori feasts - but to explain how their actions were all part of a huge system of communication: travel, contributing together to feasts, gifts.

\par 
\par Tawney}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15750707  introduced his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid15750707\charrsid15750707 Primitive Economy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15750707  book}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  because Postan and Eileen Power showed him the manuscript.  Knew Tawney }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3695198 but not closely.  Firth was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  abroad}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3695198  at that time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .
\par 
\par Knew Eileen Power very well: admired and respected, charming and beautiful.  A descriptive rather than theoretical intellectual, much influenced by Postan. Was a witness at their wedding. He gave her theoretical dynamism as well as seeing her as a woman. 
 One of three feminist sisters, especially Rhoda Power, the youngest.  Eileen very attractive, relished but did not yield to it, could have married several times.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Primitive Economics of the New Zealand Maori}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  is the first systematic attempt to put Maori mat
erial together within a theoretical framework, and the first to focus on Maori economy rather than religion etc.  Reprinted by the New Zealand Government Printer in 1957, dropping }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Primitive}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  from the title, by then old-fashioned.
\par 
\par Already interested in soci
al change.  At the end of the book there is a whole section on the changes following the arrival of Europeans.  The social change perspective was a contribution, because of the then influence in British anthropology of diffusion theory, as with Elliott Sm
i
th and Perry.  Daryll Forde his colleague was for a while Perry's assistant and apostle.  He set himself against this.  Divided later Maori period into four phases: initial contact with Europeans; early influence from them; reaction as they lost their lan
ds; and re-adaptation.
\par 
\par At LSE also Frederick Brown, statistician, and wife Agnes, friends of his and Malinowski.  Small parties.  Pearl Binder, artist, flamboyant, became socialist grande dame, Lady Elwyn Jones.  Victor della Torre, founded Peruvian social
ist party, belonged to the seminar.  Went to Paris with Victor, Pearl and Hortense Powd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4927862 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 rmaker.
\par 
\par Met Mauss with Malinowski, and later in England.  Had been an interpreter in the war with New Zealand troops and picked up some Maori.  Was reviving }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 L'Ann\'e9e sociologique}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
, which both Malinowski and he admired.  Mauss a skilful cook, and pleasant.
\par 
\par Talcott Parsons was mainly working with L. T. Hobhouses's social philosophy seminar, but also came over to Malinowski's seminar.  Got to know him very well.  His functi
onalism was developed independently of Malinowski.  He is less keen on Parsons' Freudianism: it was the fashion then for every American academic to be psychoanalysed - Kluckholm, Parsons.  Admires }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9000958 The Structure of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Social Action,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  interdisciplinary, but did not come to much.
\par 
\par Very aware of Freud, and has read a lot.  A great man.  One does not have to accept his theories to be interested in his methods.  Controversy about authority of mother's brother between Ernest Jones and Malinowski, thinks the latter rig
ht.  There were big debates about Freudianism at LSE in 1920s.
\par 
\par Karl Marx a bad politician but a great sociologist.  Calls himself a Marxian, not a Marxist.  But did not read Marx until later.  Does not remember big debates about Marxism in 1920s.
\par 
\par Does not remember Postan as a Marxist.  Walked, climbed and talked together a lot in the Cotswolds and Wales.
\par 
\par Feminism not an issue.  In anthropology people were appointed for their merits not their sex: among women, Audrey Richards, Lucy Mair, Lorriane Barie,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9000958  M
argaret Rea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 d were all people of importance.  There was no need for feminism.
\par 
\par Keeps in touch with Maori issues through Dame Joan Metge, long annual letter, and Professor Hugh Kawharu.
\par 
\par First stayed in London in a hotel, then lodged with a Boots store mana
ger in Hendon, view of fields with sheep.  Eating Chinese food in Limehouse Causeway, and Indian at Shafi's in Gerrard Street.  Not then much music, though had had home sung Bach in New Zealand.  Not much theatre.  Went to ballet, influenced by Postan: }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12674885\charrsid12674885 Diaghilev}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 Ballet, Lydia Lopokova danced, who later married Keynes.
\par 
\par Special women friends at that time Camilla Wedgwood, Hortense Powdermaker, Agnes Brown, Pearl Binder.  Mixed groups walking around Guildford.
\par 
\par Chose to study Tikopia as a Polynesian community
 at an earlier stage of development.  First considered Rennell Island, larger, also in Solomons, but that ruled out as a target for mining phosphate, and Radcliffe-Brown had already sent a student there, Ian Hogbin.  Met the missionary Durrad who had star
t
ed work on Tikopian language.  Also had information from the mission ship which called every year or two, that Tikopia very simple technologically, and very isolated.  Went back first to New Zealand, via Sydney to make contact with Radcliffe-Brown.  Some 
months at home, then Sydney, then monthly passenger steamer to Solomons to capital Tulagi 500 miles from Tikopia, then the mission vessel }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid284431 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid284431 Southern Cross}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid284431 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 seven weeks round other islands, ti
ll put down in Tikopia with his stores - jam, biscuits, tobacco, clay pipes, steel adzes, which had heard would be welcome.
\par 
\par Had taken an adze given by his father by house-building, which the Tikopia thought very interesting for canoe building, so wrote to his father, and three months later the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid284431 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid284431 Southern Cross}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid284431 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 returned with more supplies including adzes.  Didn't return for another nine months, two months late: with no radio, they didn't know why the ship hadn't come.
\par 
\par Not lonely, in that surrounded by peop
le, and so absorbed that he didn't miss the company of people like himself.  But had to be completely self-reliant.  Anxiety when he was investigating their religion, and wondered whether they might club him.  Worried about health: at one point very ill f
or three weeks.
\par 
\par Grant from Australian National Research Council, chaired by Radcliffe-Brown.  Also sent Fortune to Dobu, Hogbin to Java.  Laura Spellman Rockefeller Fund was supporting social science.  
\par 
\par Choice of Tikopia his own.  But it was assumed at Malinowski's seminar that all students would undertake a sustained period of fieldwork.  Knowledge of Maori was a linguistic advantage for him.
\par 
\par Importing steel tools did not alter the economy because Tikopia had long given up their own clam shell blades.  No local stone, all stone tools were imported.  From mid-19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 century occasional vessels called, so a very few metal tools were introduced.
\par 
\par Most important early influence from American anthropology was Lowie's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Primitive Society.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781   Kroeber and Kluckholm late
r.  Boas respected, but seen as old-fashioned.  Working on the Indian Reserves through old men's memories was a very restricted way of doing anthropology.  What is the role of life history in social science? Memory is treacherous.  Life histories have to 
be looked at sceptically, including his own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid284431 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 In 1925-6 for some months worked half time as Malinowski'}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11036899 s research assistant, for \'a32-10}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 a week, working closely with him on article on culture for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Encyclopaedia Britannica}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 . Argued with him a lot about the text.  Also about kinship structures.
\par 
\par Radcliffe-Brown was anthropology professor in Sydney and chair of the anthropology committee of the Australian National Research Council, looking for active young anthropologists to come out as researchers.   He wrote to R
adcliffe-Brown, who provided the money, but took no practical part.  Arranged the stores himself, 20 cases, including steel tools, fish hooks - idea from the Melanesian mission.  Rev. Durrad had been there for some months in 1910 but could do no anthropol
ogy because the ship brought an infection: hence it was mainly a mourning time.  From Durrad knew that the Tikopia had no money.  Met Durrad in retirement in New Zealand.
\par 
\par Contrast between the colonial Resident and District Commissioners, who spoke no local languages, and the mission people, who all spoke New Hebridean Mota, and in some cases also the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11036899  local vernaculars.  Three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  important books}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11036899  by}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
: Codrington, Ivens, and the saintly Canon Fox, who settled among the Melanesians.  So they knew much more about the people that the government administrative officers.
\par 
\par Different languages between each island and often within them.  Polynesian dialects mutually intelligible, but Melanesian languages not.
\par 
\par Has written nine books and forty articles on Tikopia, with different objectives.  On first visit in 1928-9 studying a traditional society, kinship, religion, and collecting about everything because might never return: for example, did collect history.

\par 
\par Second time 1952 with invaluable colleague James Spillius, to look at change.  Tikopia migrating abroad for plantation work, and sending back goods, although still not using much money.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11036899 Stay: }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Seven months.
\par 
\par Third time 1966 with Torben Monberg, who has studied Polynesian island of Bellona, to study especially religious change.  Most islanders had been pagan in 1928-9 and still a sector in 1952, but in 1966 all Christian. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11036899 Stay:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  A month.
\par 
\par Fourth time 1973 for the Tikopia dictionary with Pa Rangiaco, who was teaching on Ugi; 1978 got him to Auckland, so they worked on it together.
\par 
\par First visit made him rethink his moral views: saw the need for in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13575250 fanticide when food }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 short.  Also came to understand that there was little pure generosity.  If the Tikopia gave to him, 
it was reasonable that they should hope for something in return.  He was a stranger among them, with huge quantities of steel tools, axes, knives, fish hooks, so why should they not try to get them, with gifts of mats as symbols of affection.  Eventually 
b
ecame quite open, that those who gave him information about religion would be rewarded, and that those who gave the best information would receive the best gifts of affection. These were mostly the chiefs and elders, but they were afraid the gods would pu
nish them if they spoke.
\par 
\par Extract from his diary on early weeks.  Anger and cursing when he is given land for a house.  Neighbours pretend they have forgotten names of their ancestors.  Scared also of photos taking the soul of kava.  Eventually developed a 
real friendship with chief's son Pa }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid271642\charrsid271642 Fenuatara}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , to whom dedicated 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Social Change in Tikopia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
, very intelligent.
\par 
\par Three cameras.  Newman Guardia quarter plate; Graphlex reflex taking postcard size film; and ordinary hand-held camera.  Problems with developing due to lack of ice.  Processed them while in Tikopia.  
\par 
\par Tikopia called him the chief who writes down what people say.  Later, the younger generations regarded him as knowledgeable about their own past.  N}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16213937 
ames, first the stranger; then \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Fosi', Firth; later friend, brother, father or grandfather.
\par 
\par They did soon understand what he was doing.  Initially highly suspicious, but always courteous.
\par 
\par The chief's son, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12538180\charrsid13782781 Pa }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid271642\charrsid271642 Fenuatara}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , was very handsome.  Cured him of ringworm. Long hair.  Gardener, fisherman.  Talked widely, including family and domestic life.
\par 
\par One of elders, Pa Sao, a family elder, perverse and rough-tongued, beat his son, but an active pagan and gave first vital clues to the ritual system.
\par 
\par Second visit in 1952 coincided with a serious famine which was the sequel to a tropical hurricane.  Despite food shortages, still invited to meals: overt social discipline was maintained.  But much covert stealing.
\par 
\par On first visit
 accompanied by servant boy Vahihaloa, lively, spoke another Polynesian dialect but soon picked up Tikopia, and spent much time with unmarried islanders.  Ran his household, organising receiving and sending out of food gifts.  Had been sent by J.C. Barley
, the only Commissioner who spoke the vernacular and equally unusually had married a Polynesian.
\par 
\par Did not take a mistress himself, but was assigned to the group of bachelors and maidens, and talked a lot in the evenings with them, jokes, songs, gossip.  The
 experience of this broadened his mind on sex.  Taking a mistress would not have been dangerous, but it would have been inexpedient, in giving him a special relationship to one family, and so at a disadvantage with others.  Not on, from a scientific point
 of view.
\par 
\par Note-taking with daily diary in sections: weather, myself, people, food.  Food details later showed seasonal changes.  No
tebooks for recording one-to-one interviewees and general conversation - could write very fast, and keen to get down the language.  Wrote on the spot, not in the evenings.  Better to spend evening talking.
\par 
\par Household census of the whole island, which prove
d invaluable when he returned with Spillius, so able, with demographer Borrie, to write a paper on population changes.  Also collected ethnographical objects for a museum in Australia.  Maps of land holdings, again later used to study change.
\par 
\par House, at fi
rst the Mission School, built of coral boulders and thatch.  After some months, to other side of the island, lived in a typical thatched house with not full-size doorway so you crawled in, with mat walls, about 12 feet square, one room.  Vahihaloa cooked 
outside on an earth oven, food wrapped in leaves; and he slept away with his friends.
\par 
\par Chest with personal possessions, and a camp bed, two chairs and a card table.  Used to camping in New Zealand.  When the mission ship was late, had to tie up his broken shoes with wire, and used wire to thread his notebooks.
\par 
\par Water had to be carefully piped through flues of palm tree trunks. Showered in the open with the local men.
\par 
\par To sum up first visit, the year gave him a new perspective on civilisation.  He could now s
ee how a completely different way of functioning could be effective and satisfying.  Gave him a feeling of the relativity of values.  Not a cultural relativist in the sense that anything is as good as another: there is always a need to balance individual 
desires and the need for social co-operation.  But because there are differences in customs, there are different ways of meeting these needs.
\par 
\par Second visit in 1952 was at a time of food shortage and disorder. Distressed to see palms shorn of their fronds.  
Yet given a remarkable welcome.  Mutual delight in being with Pa Fenuatara after 23 years.  They liked Spillius, who stayed on for a longer period.  Dances abbreviated because of Arika Kafika's illness, but saw an abbreviated version.  Became ill, and had
 
to be taken off by ship to the New Hebrides for penicillin.  This time had a radio, run by Spillius, and therefore also able to get relief supplies of rice which the government asked them to arrange to distribute, which they did, household by household.  
Government unable to work with the chiefs because they spoke no English.  
\par 
\par James Spillius a Canadian Greek, delightful, still in touch. Met in Sydney,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3700320  was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  given a free meal in a Greek restaurant.  
\par 
\par Tikopia were on the threshold of modernity.  Men already going abroad for labour, government beginning to manifest its control.  Did a new household census.
\par 
\par Not so interested in changing gender roles.  This time some women were handling canoes.  Women had always been important, had rank, but not power, no priests.  As they got work, that changed.
\par 
\par Soon got used to young women being bare to the waist, within a few days.  Gauguin is a favou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15757392 rite, but he was a romantic.  Gauguin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  did have real relationships with Polynesian women, but his images are romanticised, and he didn't understand how local society worked.
\par 
\par Sees himself as in a way a romantic, in that fascinated by the exotic.  Reads a lot on Japan and China too.  You can be a sceptical romantic.
\par 
\par The books which he took to Tikopia included Gogol's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Dead Souls}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Oxford Bo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8024273 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 k of German Verse.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781   No Bible, no Shakespeare, no poetry.  Few novels - Rosemary reads better ones - but has read Dickens, Kipling, Alec Waugh; favourites Austen and Trollope.
\par 
\par Third visit in 1966 was with Torben Monberg, a Dane, who is now the authority on Western Polynesia.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8024273   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
Professor of anthropology in Copenhagen.  Studied Rennell and Bellona, and has kept in touch with Bellona, and taken his family there many times.  Met before first went to Bellona; charming man.  Rosemary had been against 
this third visit.  Pagan ceremonies had now completely ceased.  Previous visit, people thought of the gods as in retirement, but still there, and could be invoked.  Saw Christianity as simply incorporating local gods.  Now more sophisticated, and a priest
 from Tikopia has become a bishop.  Visiting the old pagan sites was melancholy.  In the future perhaps will see old religious accounts as their history.
\par 
\par Himself a humanist.  Only three of his nine Tikopia books focus on religion: }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 The Work of t
he Gods; Tikopia Ritual and Belief; Rank and Religion in Tikopia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .  Lists them: others on kinship }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 (We, the Tikopia)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , economics }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8024273 (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Primitive Polynesian Economy)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , social change }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 (Social Change in Tikopia)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , tradition work }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 (History and Traditions of Tikopia)}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , and language and song }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
(Tikopia Dictionary; Tikopia Songs)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .
\par 
\par Contribution of his economic analysis was to show that a non-monetary society had an economic system.  Next stage was studied in Malaysia.  In Tikopia the system was not barter, as orthodox economists
 predicted, but giving: grumbling perhaps, but no haggling.  Very complex balances between material gifts and services; and at the peak, land rights, adjudicated by the chief and elders.  Marx was wrong in thinking you could not have exchange value in suc
h a society.
\par 
\par Weakness of most economic writing is in ignoring the social context.  Emotion can also affect economics: for instance, in Malay society, if a man gets angry when bargaining.  Economists have failed to observe people bargaining.  Also wanted to
 introduce models of social obligation.
\par 
\par Dictionary: stayed with Ishmael Tuki in 1973 and worked then on the language, and then separately until met in Auckland in 1978, and published Tikopia/English dictionary in 1985.  But he wanted English/Tikopia, and 
Andrew Pawley of Australian National University began work on this two years ago, and it's almost ready for publication.  Hopes it will help the younger men to keep up interest in their language.
\par 
\par Has long believed that his field notebooks and diary should
 be treated as a historical source, a better guide retrospectively than memory.  It seemed to him years ago that anthropologists might be called to account, to show they had not invented what they had described.  Feels very strongly than anthropologists s
hould keep archives.  Donald Miller is another anthropologist who agrees.  This is why he has given his material to LSE.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8024273\charrsid13782781 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Home to New Zealand for some time, then to Sydney as a lecturer for Radcliffe-Brown.  Camilla Wedgwood had held the post for a year whi
le he was in Tikopia.  There three years, and after 18 months Radcliffe-Brown went to Chicago, leaving him as acting professor.  Also acting editor of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Oceania}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
, acting chair of anthropology committee of ANRC.  Salary rose from \'a3500 to \'a3900pa, felt luxurious
.  Made an important group of friends, mostly living in Bohemian area of King's Cross: Radcliffe-Brown, and Herman Adam a cultivated Swiss wool buyer; Elizabeta Germanovna, a German Russian who married another frie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8024273 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 d Vict
or Trikojus, a chemist; Otto Stern, Austrian ex-cavalry officer.  A multi-lingual, multi-cultural group; dined and danced and went to concerts and celebrated Easter together with Russian cake.  Radcliffe-Brown's apartment was a hotel ballroom so danced th
ere.
\par 
\par Radcliffe-Brown started off as A. R. Brown.  Was educati}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15695429 on director of Tonga before Syd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 ney chair.  He and Malinowski the twin founders of British social anthropology.  Very different in temperament, Radcliffe-Brown posing as an English gentleman, wide
ly read in English and French but not in other languages.  Strongly influenced by Durkheim: at one time social solidarity was his keyword.  Emphasis on structure, while Malinowski emphasised function - so RF tried to put both together.  Fine taste; played
 piano in his ballroom, not very well.  Social lion in Sydney, a Government House guest.  Very private life, with a wife and daughter in England whom he never saw.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 The Andaman Islanders}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 made a strong influence; remembers reading the chapter on method aloud
 to Malinowski, who said he might have written it himself, the highest praise.  But very wary of each other. When R-B went from Chicago to Oxford in 1937 he became a very powerful influence, especially on Evans-Pritchard.  Friends called him Rex.  Had a t
ouch of pride.
\par 
\par No graduates, but undergraduates included Phyllis Kaberry, William Stanner, Ralph Piddington, and became responsible for their field projects.
\par 
\par Occasion when forced despite protests to cancel scholarship for Malinowski's student }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5716850\charrsid5716850 Kirchhoff}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , because the British government thought he was a Communist, in 1931/2: in fact it was his wife.  No other real difficulty.
\par 
\par Malinowski wrote in 1932 saying he had always hoped he'd return, and offering a lectureship at LSE.  Australian corrugated iron and barbed wire to European cathedrals.  Left end of 1932, reaching London 1933.  Salary dropped from \'a3900 a year to \'a3
500, but never regretted it.  Two years a lecturer, then a reader, and worked with Malinowski until he left for America in 1938.
\par 
\par Married Rosemary in 1936.  First met in 1935 at Gargoyle Club, a dance club: }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13702897 Eileen Power, Munia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  Postan and Elizabeth Drew (literary, Cambridge cousin of Rosemary) were members, Eileen was ill, so Elizabeth asked Rosemary, who was just getting a first in economics at Ed
inburgh.  Found her very attractive, went on from there.  Married over 60 years, one of the most important influences in his life.  Temperamentally very different, so vigorous, even bitter arguments, but a very real affection, and a stimulus and a critic.
 
 He accepts things more easily if they cannot be remedied.  She reads only good things, doesn't touch light fiction, he is omnivorous.  He likes mediaeval music, she likes Beethoven and Brahms, both like Bach and Mozart.  Neither like jazz or modern music
, although do like Britten, and recently Lutaslawski.  She likes opera more, used to go twice weekly.  On his work, she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10422218\charrsid13782781 thinks}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  he writes too much, and his style could be better.  Sometimes argue at length over a precise word.
\par 
\par Rosemary's father a civil servant, auditor general KCB, very quiet and scholarly.  Her mother died when she was 16.
\par 
\par Previously had published }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Art and Life in New Guinea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , approached by William Gaunt, editor of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Studio}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .  Longstanding interest in Maori carving, and then in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12674885\charrsid13782781 Romanesque}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  sculp
ture.  Was also interested in modern art: read Clive Bell, Roger Fry, liked Picasso, Braque, Cubism, Paul Klee.  Earlier, Breughel.  Always interested by pattern.
\par 
\par At LSE replaced C.G. Seligman, who was an all-round ethnologist, and looked after stones and bones, so for first two or three years lectured on prehistoric anthropology, which was not his field.
\par 
\par Active social life after married Rosem
ary in June 1936.  Seligman invited them to home in Toot Baldon with magnificent collection of Tang and Sung Chinese porcelain, gave them a bowl as a wedding present.  Many social occasions with Audrey Richards (admirable, wise woman, though never a profe
s
sor, director of East African Institute); Lucy Mair (more political, later worked with Lord Hailey); Gordon Childe, archaeologist; Prince Peter of Greece and Denmark (anthropologist, polyandry in Tibet).  Many came to seminars, including Jomo Kenyatta, wh
o read a paper on magic, and seemed to really believe in its efficacy.
\par 
\par Edmund Leach also a friend, the most brilliant of anthropologists after Malinowski.  Perhaps too brilliant, for example his study of the Sistine Chapel paintings is over-speculative.  T
echnically his research assistant for a while, respected each other.  Later a very successful as provost of King's.
\par 
\par Remembers wearing old-fashioned long coat and striped trousers to visit Rosemary's cousin who was an Eton housemaster.
\par 
\par Then living in Bloomsbury, came to Highgate 1953, after a whole sequence of moves.
\par 
\par Secretary of the Royal Anthropological Institute, then very formal: remembers a lecturer on Fiji textiles wearing black tie and dinner dress.  Has changed very radically since.  A kind of clu
b, was then in Bloomsbury.  Transfer of the library to the British Museum.  RAI has always included many non-academics.  Up until 1945 was the main focus for British anthropologists, but then in 1946 led by Evans-Pritchard the Association of Social Anthro
pologists was set up, initially with 30 members, all trained by Malinowski or Radcliffe-Brown.  Now over 500 members.  Originally proposed to hive off completely, but did keep cross-membership with RAI, and two institutions co-operate.
\par 
\par Applied for anthropology chair at Cambridge in 1937, but turned down in favour of Hutton, ex-colonial officer who had written about the Nagas of Assam and was thought more practical-minded.  Rosemary had not wanted him to go.
\par 
\par Member, as Secretary-of-State's request, of colonial education advisory committee, the first of many such memberships.
\par 
\par In 1938 research assistant was W.E.H. Stanner, highly respected Australian social anthropologist also trained in economics, good theoretical mind.
\par 
\par Cottage near Thorncombe bought in 1937 by Rosemary, and spent much of summer 1938 there writing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Human Types.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
  Title given by publishers Nelson.  Purpose to show to ordinary readers how people in other cultures could behave reasonably, although their behaviour seemed odd to us: e.g. European w
omen wore skirts, Chinese women wore trousers; Europeans shake hands, Polynesians rub noses. 
\par 
\par An important purpose was to destroy racist notions.  A book of its time: threat of war looming, and anthropologists all anti-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2900780\charrsid13782781 Nazi}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , anti-racist.  Remembers travelling in Germany, anti-Jewish notices, absolutely abhorrent. In American South, landing at Newp}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2900780 ort News, did not realise what \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
white waiting room' meant, thought it was the paint colour.  Washington in 1942 still Jim Crow attitudes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2900780\charrsid13782781 Negroes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  at the back of t
he bus.  Visited Franklin Frazier there, and shocked to realise that as a black he could not go into bars in downtown Washington.  Never went to South Africa; had no wish to.
\par 
\par Would have gone to China, to work with anthropology professor in Beijing, Wu Wen
 Tsao, former LSE student, but the Japanese got there first: so did not go there for 40 years.  Had started Mandarin by linguaphone, but switched to Malay.  Learnt with Sir Richard Winstedt in London. Just a beginning, because they spoke a strong dialect 
in north-eastern Malaya. In fact war did break out while they were there.  Returned by way of Australia and New Zealand at end of 1940.
\par 
\par Went out to Singapore in a passenger-cargo vessel, and through contacts of Rosemary's family stayed in beautiful old hou
se of colonial secretary.  Then to Kelantan, semi-independent north-eastern state.  Had a Malay style house built for them, thatch roof with palm growing through, plaited bamboo walls, view of sea, two rooms with kitchen at the back.  Malay servant couple
 cooked, Mahmud and Che Mbong; she cooked magnificent Malay food, had worked for a Rajah.  They lived at the back.
\par 
\par They were primarily studying the economic aspects of local life.  He focussed on production and marketing, Rosemary on consumption and domestic side.  Sees their books as complementary, his on the techniques and economics of fishing, Rosemary's }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Housekeeping Among Malay Peasants}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 a rare study of domestic management. Men's activities have been much more studied than women's.
\par 
\par In Tikopia, alone, he got a lot of material on men and some on women, but in Malaya alone he could have got much less on women.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2900780 
With Rosemary, who had access enabled them to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  discuss together what the husband said and what the wife said.
\par 
\par Trusted informants 
included Awang Long, master fisherman, friend as well as informant, religious, moral.  Rosemary had a particular friend Che Yoh, the wife of a fisherman.  On return visits, received with considerable affection by friends.  When they were leaving, gave a s
pecial three-night entertainment, ritual drama, shadow play, as a way of thanking the village.
\par 
\par Outside the village, friends included `the four musketeers', one later a director of education, and Nik Mustafa, district commissioner, the four leading young me
n in the state.  British civil servants usually spoke Malay well and knew about Malay society, like De Moubray, who had published book on Malay matrilineal family, so sympathetic; also a planter, Bangs, who employed Malay labour and showed they could be g
ood workers, not just lazy and impulsive.  But most Europeans did not know Malay and had arrogant and contemptuous attitudes towards Malays.
\par 
\par Did not believe that they could gain more practical information that skilled resident colonial civil servants, but a possible role in showing economic system.  Nobody had illustrated the bargaining process.
\par 
\par Observed traditional drumming, learned magical formulae relating to Malay rather than Moslem beliefs: Djinn spirits and colours, success, illness.  Taught by spirit healer Tok Mamat Mindok.  Watched sacrifice of bull at Hari Rava Haji festival. 
\par 
\par Didn't publish all they intended: dropped plan for a book on agriculture.  On spiritual side, imagination most caught by shadow play.
\par 
\par Third visit in 1963, looked at change, motor boats, purse seine nets, fish taken to market with ice rather than sold on the beach.  Chinese capital behind re-equipment.
\par 
\par Fourth visit, 1979, first signs that the role of women was changing: wives taken abroad, and local radio announcer a woman.  Datin Azizah is important in Malay social and economic institute.
\par 
\par Second visit had been in 1947 for Colonial Social Science Research Council, to advise on research plans, two years after Japanese had gone: toured around in a weapon carrier.  Independence, which he favoured, was looming.
\par 
\par Explains about listening to fish, not magical, a genuine physical hearing skill.
\par 
\par Local suppliers of credit in 1939 were wealthier village men, but not necessarily leaders.
\par 
\par Cost of the project: he was on half salary for the year, \'a3300, plus a Leverhulme grant of \'a3500.
\par 
\par Second World War and Colonial Social Science Research Council, 1940-1945
\par 
\par Left Malaysia late 1940 after the fall of France, by Sydney and New Zealand. From Wellington on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4021954 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid4021954 Rangitiki}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4021954 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid4021954  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
cargo liner: one first class passenger, a dozen second class including themselves, and third class marines.  Through Panama Canal to Halifax where joined a convoy escorted by converted merchant ship HMS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4021954 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid4021954 Jervis Bay}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4021954 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  with six inch guns and no armour plating
.  On 5 November over the horizon saw the topmasts of a German pocket cruiser the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4021954 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid4021954 Admiral Scheer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4021954 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  which fired at the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid4021954 Rangitiki}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , and then the little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid4021954 Jervis Bay}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  steered for her, six inch guns against eleven inch, most moving, soon burning furiously, sank within two hours.  Perhaps because had been recently refitted, }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid4021954 Scheer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 kept her distance, and only nine of 38 in convoy were lost.  Very tense time.  Headed for Rockall, but submarines there, so for Liverpool Roads, finally ashore at Milford Haven.  Probably the most frightening experience in his life.
\par 
\par Stayed with Rosemary's father and stepmother in London; nights in sandbagged cellars.  LSE evacuated to Cambridge, so briefly there.
\par 
\par Recruited into naval intelligence - NID 5, geographical intelligence: was invited to join.  Was British citizen as a New Zealander.  Did give some lectures, but time mostly at the Scott Polar Research Institute, centre for producing geographical intellige
n
ce in the form of maps and books for the navy. Naval Intelligence Director was Admiral Godfrey.  Assigned to the Pacific, and produced four volumes, but after the war was over; reports and maps more immediately.  Assistant was Jim Davidson, later Pacific 
h
istory professor at ANU, remarkable man.  Around 30 or 40 worked in the Institute, with Clifford Darby, geographer, as director, and J.M. Wordie as liaison with the navy. Also interpreter for Polynesian languages, mainly reading letters from French sailor
s, rarely interesting except when one ship seemed to be heading for Africa instead of the Pacific.
\par 
\par Rosemary at the Board of Trade.
\par 
\par Sailed to America 1942 in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4021954 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid4021954 Queen Mary}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4021954 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
, arriving in Boston: problem at immigration.  In Washington to examine geographical intelligence on the Pacific - 17 different organisations, some very bad, the engineers best.  Several interesting weeks in Washington. Returned by Liberator flight.

\par 
\par In 1944 released by Navy to join Colonial Research }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2430002 Committee, at suggestion of Aud}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 rey Richa
rds who had been working with Lord Hailey: in the midst of war, planning post-war research.  His job was to get people out onto the field on significant problems.  Visited West Africa for three months 1945: Gambia, Sierra Leone, Gold Cost, Nigeria, findin
g
 out how officers and local people saw the main agricultural, economic and social problems.  Also looked at files.  Colonial governments had been asked for suggestions on research but gave almost none.  Was only briefly secretary, until LSE demanded him b
ack, and his successors Paul Wilson and Sally Chilver were both very effective.  Continued as a member of the Council: Malaya visit 1947 (but not New Guinea 1951).
\par 
\par In Malaya, collected material much in same way as Tikopia.  Tried to record vernacular expre
ssions.  Some systematic observation, for example of fishing yields.  Would write on the scene, for example on the beach while people were unloading.  Also photographs important.  Recorded their own discussions too.
\par 
\par Of the people who worked for the Colonial Social Science Research Council, the most notable was Edmund Leach, who went to Sarawak: preferred him to the government ethnologist of Sarawak Tom Harrison, who took a long time to forgive him.
\par 
\par Leach like himself has a long interest in social change.  Extraordinary war experiences in Burma, where was leader of the Kachin guerrillas behind the Japanese lines, walked to Kunming, and finally reached India.  When he returned, he as}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11037306 k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 ed what he could do since the Japanese had destroyed all his }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11037306\charrsid13782781 field notes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , b
ut combined his own knowledge of custom with historical material to study social change in the Burmese highlands.
\par 
\par Also got an outsider, R.R. Kuczynski, involved in the Jamaica census.  Knew Edith Clarke very well: vigorous researcher, active minded, practical more than theoretical, white Jamaican.
\par 
\par Charles Madge and Tom Harrison had come to one or two seminars with Malinowski, who told them they needed to be more rigorous and systematic and come to more seminars; but did write one of their prefaces.  Madge
 went on to be a sociology professor but Harrison couldn't be an academic, although his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Savage Civilisation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  about the New Hebrides is quite remarkable.  Has written an article on the defects of Mass Observation: listening to what people say in pubs doesn't
 go far without theory.
\par 
\par LSE had been occupied by the Ministry of Economic Warfare, and at the end of the war stuffed full of books like a sand dune with camels' bones sticking out.  Carr Saunders held fortnightly meetings on how to rebuild LSE both struct
urally and intellectually.
\par 
\par Department of Anthropology soon began to build up staff, and by 1950 at least six.  Isaac Schapera joined from South Africa in 1951, had been professor in Cape Town: worked together for 17 years very amicably, deciding by consul
tation.  Notable staff included Margaret Read, Audrey R}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2054853 ich}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 ards, Edmund Leach, Lorraine Lancaster/Baric - quite a number of women.
\par 
\par With the help of a gift from Leach started LSE Monographs in Social Anthropology, now over 60 volumes.  The first his own }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Work of the Gods}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , no 7 Rosemary, no 4 Evans-Pritchard.  Paul Stirling converted it to proper print form; originally typed and photocopied.
\par 
\par Set up a student anthropological library, the Seligman Library, with a starting gift from Brenda Seligman.
\par 
\par Decided needed to commemorate Malinowski, whose memory was under attack by Radcliffe-Brown and Evans-Pritchard's denigrations.  Set up a lectureship, and published a commemorative volume.
\par 
\par Lecturing had grown, but the key still the Friday seminar and the intercollegiate seminar, first run by Daryll Forde from University College.  Department had started with only graduates; first two undergraduates 1938-9, women; also undergraduates and othe
rs - such as Kenyatta - doing a diploma.  Subsequently increasingly undergraduates.
\par 
\par Many Commonwealth students: Phylllis Kaberry, Stanner, Ralph Piddington from Australia; Joan Metge from New Zealand; from India, Aiyappan (study of his own Irava caste, and caste relationships; later director of Madras Museum).
\par 
\par Never formally head, just two professors who ran the department together 1944-68.  Only more recently a designated department convenor.
\par 
\par Invitation from Dr Coombs of Australian government 1947 to act
 as consultant for Pacific Studies school of new Australian National University in Canberra.  Went out 1948 with Rosemary and son Hugh, with possibility of staying on, although always dubious about this.
\par 
\par Volume on Malinowski, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Man and Culture}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , includes a p
iece by Meyer Fortes.  A great friend, highly intelligent, trained as a psychologist; moved into anthropology under influence of Malinowski; alter closely associated with Evans-Pritchard and Radcliffe-brown.  Very good fieldworker in Ghana.
\par 
\par Malinowski's dislike of sham: on serious matters, he liked to lay things on the table.
\par 
\par Australian National University: organised a conference to try to define the field of Pacific Studies. Kept his connection until 1952.  Appointed James Davidson, Siegfried Nadel and O
skar Spate as professors of history, anthropology and geography. 1951 visit with Davidson and Spate to Papua New Guinea to see research opportunities. With difficulty finally decided 1951 to return, but went to Tikopia 1952 under ANU auspices.  Drawn back
 by kin and friends.  Revisited 1964 for honorary degree, 1972 as research fellows, last visit 1979, but went to a graduates' meeting in London 1999.
\par 
\par Never applied for LSE chair, simpl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5659936 y appointed by Carr }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Saunders in 1944. Had taken up duties there in 1946, salary \'a31500.
\par 
\par That year took time off for health reasons and visited Engadine in Switzerland, spoke Ladinish.  Beautiful }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5659936\charrsid13782781 Romanesque}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  paintings in Zillis church.  Son Hugh born in December, enormously important thing.
\par 
\par Elected Fellow of the British Academy in 1949, which rather prizes.
\par 
\par Began lecturing abroad in 1956, New York, Wenner-Gren Foundation: later they did conferences in an Austrian castle.  Knew Talcott Parsons: offer of chair 1953, turned down easily.
\par 
\par With Basil Yamy, 1960, chaired a conference on economic anthropology, interdisciplinary, published as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Capital, Saving and Credit}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 .  1959 for eight months at Institute of Advanced Studies in Palo Alto, 40-odd people, nine anthropologists.
\par 
\par First contact with Russian anthropology was Ivan Potekin at International Conference on Anthropology at Philadelphia 1956.  He was interesting and frank but more political, had no knowledge of social anthropology or sociology.
\par 
\par Revisit to Malaya in 1963, including re-survey of village, reported in second editions of their books.
\par 
\par First honorary degree Oslo 1965.
\par 
\par New Guinea, 1951, on the fringe of an untapped world: met at airstrip by men bare to the waist armed with spears and clubs.  Erosion and food supply.  Excitement of flying in small planes.  Took photographs, including one on the cover of }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Human Types.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Honorary degree at Krakow, 1984, was really as Malinowski's surrogate.
\par 
\par Committee work on new technology with UNESCO: chaired one in Kyrenia.  Connections with conferences on public health in Geneva and Amsterdam.  Leiden ceremony where Rosemary had to pretend to be a man.  Around 1950, in Brussels advising
 Belgians on training colonial staff.
\par 
\par Contacts with WHO started through Scottish public health Dr Brotherston, at Bloomsbury institute, with whom ran a joint conference.
\par 
\par United Nations conference in New York 1953, committee on standards of living, chaire
d at his suggestion by Indian economist V.R.V.K. Rao.  Same year, WHO conference on child mental health in Sydney.  Then 1953 with WHO for a week in Tokyo, visiting the country with Ronald Walker, Australian economist and ambassador.  Juxtaposition of tra
ditional and new.
\par 
\par Social Science Research Council: Research and Teaching in Britain; 
\par Theories of Social Science
\par 
\par Invited by Michael Young 1965 to become a member of Social Science Research Council, and became chairman of anthropology committee for several years, continuing the earlier activities of the Colonial Social Science Research Council.
\par 
\par Liked Michael Young: novel-minded, not eccentric, ideas of his own.  Good chairman, open-minded.  Had known him from work at Institute of Community Studies (like Peter Townsend).  Michael called him a mentor.  Have good relations.
\par 
\par Some association with the Royal Society: committees, and groups, on non-verbal communication, population.  Leach and J.R. Fox also involved.
\par 
\par At same time, at LSE the two weekly seminars, and administration.  Long working days, worked evenings and weekends.
\par 
\par In inaugural lecture in 1946, never published, argued that the subject of anthropology was not primitive cultures, but people on the fringe of the industrial world.  And the significanc
e of history, which he had always believed in, as did Schapera.  In Joseph Mason lectures at Birmingham 1947, published as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
The Elements of Social Organisation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , was trying to clarify his own view: the dialectical relationship between the individual and soci
ety, the struggles for self-interest and the needs for social conformity.
\par 
\par The need to survive means food, which means an economy.  Reproduction and the sex drive make kinship.  Thirdly, the construction of images.  His work has taken all three in turn: ec
onomics, kinship, religion.  Not new ideas at this time, but the war had brought home the impact of technological change.  Malinowski had stressed social function, Radcliffe-Brown social structure; he felt the need for a third element, social organisation
.  Then later focussed more on symbolic issues, and religion.
\par 
\par October 1947, out of a seminar group, formed a student research group on British kinship (including a New Zealander and a Chinese; Lorraine Lancaster also helped), beginning with Bermondsey, called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5659936 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Southborough' in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Two Studies in Kinship}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
, published 1956.  Combined with studies of London and Bedford Italians by Philip Garigue, a former student, later an influential professor in Montreal, had an Italian wife which gave him the entr\'e9e.  Judith Djam
our, wife of Maurice Freedman, helped to write up the material.  Non-random sample, which was criticised by Audrey Richards, because of high chance of refusals.  At Palo Alto talked with David Schneider and designed a comparative study with his team in Ch
i
cago, this time based on random samples.  Schneider had been a Chicago student, intelligent, strong opinions, fieldwork on Yap in Pacific, came 1951-3 as LSE lecturer, described Firth's seminar as like a conductor with an orchestra; went back to Berkeley.
  Tended to know the answers even before he asked the questions; but original mind.  He got money for both sides from the US Na}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5659936 tional Science Foundation.  In }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 London, small pilot sample, but then a random sample in Highgate.  Team based was Skepper House 196
0-5; he was director, Jane Hubert team leader. The book also co-written with Anthony Forge.  Dorothy Crozier a New Zealand historian looked at the local history, but a slow publisher.  Every fieldworker was given the aide memoir, developed through collect
i
ve discussion, described in the working paper.  Cannot remember exact details now.  Protected confidentiality by using pseudonyms.  Long discussions about particular family cases, and the work.  Schneider joined them for talks in 1961, and they went to Ch
i
cago to see him and Alice Rossi, sociologist who led their team.  But while enormous amount of material collected on the Chicago side, never published or used in Schneider's work, so the comparison failed.  Ray Smith did publish a book on race and kin usi
ng some of the Chicago material.
\par 
\par Anthony Forge had researched in New Guinea; intermittent role in project.
\par 
\par Much discussion on cases, and many drafts, so felt that he knew some of the families as if personally.  Also tabulated some of the answers.
\par 
\par Institute of Community Studies work on the family did not use random samples, and more concerned about public appeal they could make through their findings, while he wanted to know about kinship.  Does not think the middle class put the same emphasis on g
a
thering around mum.  But more popular writing up.  Michael Young wants to make something that works: Open University, SSRC, kinship studies not for knowledge but to do something.  In his own books includes much material, so that people might draw alternat
ive conclusions.
\par 
\par Contrast between nearby working class grandparents and often distant middle class kin.  Still convinced of the importance of kinship.  Issues include impact on kin relations of travelling for work; peer groups and leisure; single parenting
 and cohabitation.
\par 
\par Retired in 1968, but for ten years much time teaching in universities abroad: University of Hawaii, University of British Columbia, Cornell, Chicago, City University New York (1971), University of California Davis (1974), Berkeley (1977
), Auckland (1978) - his last full teaching post. In 1979 investigating Chinese anthropology on a British Academy delegation.
\par 
\par Made a Knight Bachelor in 1973, doesn't know why.
\par 
\par Continued to participate in some LSE seminars.  Students now tend to be more c
areer-orientated.  Preferred teaching through discussion: conductor of an orchestra, each instrument to play its part.  Larger seminar in which only the prima donnas sing is not his style.  Teaching a way of understanding the human condition, rather than 
a body of facts.
\par 
\par More recent writing includes papers on Marx: his usefulness to a sceptical anthropologist, and on labour theory of value, for which he read in German.  Third paper on Marx and religion.
\par 
\par Work with economists: with Basil}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11349185  Yame}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 y edited }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Capital Saving and Credit in Peasant Societies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  (1964), and book from Wenner-Gren castle conference.  Work with Stanner, and with Leonard Joy.
\par 
\par More work in linguistics.  Tikopia dictionary, for which helped by Bruce Biggs, Maori studies professor at Auckland, an
d George Milner of SOAS, linguist of Fiji and Samoa, as his mentors.  Tikopia assistant was Pa Rangiaco, whom he stayed with in 1973, and brought to Auckland 1978.  Extracted the words from his 50-odd notebooks.  Ishmael Tuki helped to refine the more dif
ficult concepts.  Published 1985.  Andrew Pawley now doing the English/Tikopia version.
\par 
\par Five years later, book on Tikopia songs also drew on old material, including recordings by Spillius in 1952.  Helped by Mervyn McLean, musicologist professor.
\par 
\par Long int
erest in art.  Paper on the Maori carver in 1925; has also written a little on Tikopia wooden sculpture, such as head rests - simple, while their poems are elaborate. But it does allow room for individual variation within the cultural form. Deep feeling f
or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11349185\charrsid13782781 Romanesque}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 sculpture and painting.  Chinese and Japanese theatre and puppets.  Talk to Oxford conference on art and anthropology organised by Jeremy Coote, published as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Art and Aesthetics in Anthropology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 (1992).  Interest in music, mediaeval to 17}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781  century; has several hundred records.
\par 
\par Not interested in music after Britten, but in visual arts was influenced by Clive Bell and Roger Fry.  Likes the work of Bridget Riley.  Picasso a mixed genius; Henry Moore hesitantly, too massive.
\par 
\par Last book is on religion, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 A Humanist Interpretation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
.  Was a Methodist, came out of Christianity into Humanism: the concept of God exists, produced by human beings.  But you cannot be certain whether or not God does exist, even if all-loving God seems improbable.  Unusual for an
 anthropologist to declare his religious position, and John Davis in his review disapproved his criticisms of Christianity.
\par 
\par This will be his last book.  But by not reading fiction in the morning, gets to the typewriter.  Had planned much of what he wanted to write in retirement.  For example }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Rank and Religion in Tikopia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
 (1970) was based on observations since 1929; the book on symbolism (1973) also begun much earlier, and then drawing from his 1970 Chicago lectures.
\par 
\par Reluctant to cho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11349185 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 se his favour
ite books.  The most translated are }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 We, The Tikopia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 Human Types.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 
\par 
\par Intellectual circle, a key sector is Rosemary.  Otherwise, in the last 30 years, Edmund Leach (opce his research assistant); William Stanner (his student in 1931); John Davis (Warden of
 All Souls, Oxford); Jonathan Benthall (director of Royal Anthropological }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11349185\charrsid13782781 Institute}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13782781\charrsid13782781 , married to daughter of Yehudi Menuhin; and neighbours, such as a Russian specialist and diplomat, and a publishing couple.  Mutual dinner parties.
\par 
\par Anthropology is in a difficult position, no practical use like accounting.
\par 
\par Son Hugh is one of his best friends: clinical psychologist.  His only local kin.  Corresponds with those in New Zealand: especially a cousin.
\par 
\par Sees his contribution to anthropology as in patient field research, great attention to detail, and capacity to integrate detail into more general patterns.  An evaluator rather than an inventor.
\par 
\par Three main achievements.  As a teacher. For the study of the complexity of a small community of 2000 people.  And for hi
s realisation of the complexity of human imagination in dealing with everyday life, including through religion.  A complexity which demands tolerance.
